[3.090, "o", "\r\nAI: The family tree shows a clear lineage:\r\n\r\n*   `sddm` (PID 967) is the display manager.\r\n*   `sddm-helper` (PID 1257) is a helper process for `sddm`.\r\n*   `start-hyprland` (PID 1309) starts the `Hyprland` window manager.\r\n*   `Hyprland` (PID 1331) is the window manager.\r\n*   `kitty` (PID 110031) is a terminal emulator.\r\n*   `zsh` (PID 110041) is the shell running within kitty.\r\n*   `python3` (PID 140180) is running the `/tmp/exfil_sim.py` script. The comm is zsh. PID 140180 is spawning many children very fast and those children are exiting very fast.\r\n\r\nThis confirms that the script was executed from a terminal session.\r\n\r\nGiven the name of the script, its location in `/tmp`, its connection to an AWS server, and the unusual shell activity, I assess that the script is highly likely to be malicious or part of a security test/simulation that was not authorized.\r\n\r\nI recommend isolating the system from the network and further investigating the script's contents using offline analysis tools. Because I cannot view the contents of the script I cannot rate the level of danger, however I strongly suspect it is trying to exfiltrate data to an AWS server.\r\n\r\n\r\n> "]
