[2.745, "o", "\r\nAI: The parent process, `zsh` (PID 141501), is also making network connections, but these do not seem to be related to the `antigravity` or `waybar` network connections. A very important file is `/home/raul/.zshrc`.\r\n\r\nIt appears the user is simply using `yazi` within a terminal. The fact that the new process is connected to google dns is a major concern and needs in-depth investigation.\r\n\r\nGiven the file access and that it spawns a Lua runtime, here's what I suspect:\r\n\r\n*   **Configuration files:** If the user has customized their `yazi` configuration files or init.lua with malicious code, it _could_ attempt to exfiltrate data or perform other malicious actions. yazi does access the users toml configurations\r\n*   **DNS queries:** Given that `yazi` is now querying DNS, the application must be resolving domain names.\r\n\r\nI am unable to read the the contents of the Lua or toml configuration files. Furthermore, I am unable to determine the domain name that yazi attempts to resolve. If I were able to get the contents of the files, and the domain name `yazi` attempts to resolve, it would help determine the root cause of the suspicious activity.\r\n\r\n> "]
