[9.544, "o", "\r\nAI: The memory maps are identical, and still show the `rwx` permissions.\r\n\r\n**I have identified a HIGH severity vulnerability: The /usr/bin/yazi binary is mapped with read, write, and execute permissions (RWX). This allows for arbitrary code injection into the process.**\r\n\r\nRecommendations:\r\n\r\n1.  **Isolate the system:** Disconnect the system from the network to prevent potential data exfiltration or further compromise.\r\n2.  **Investigate the binary:** Determine how this RWX mapping is happening. Is this intentional, or is it the result of a misconfiguration or compromise?\r\n3.  **Replace the binary:** If it's a legitimate file, obtain a clean copy from a trusted source and replace the existing one. Ensure the new copy does not have RWX permissions.\r\n4.  **Scan for malware:** Perform a full system scan with an updated antivirus solution to identify any other potential malware.\r\n5.  **Review system configurations:** Examine system configurations to identify the root cause of the issue.\r\n6.  **Examine the system code:** I am unable to execute a static analysis of the binary, but it would be essential to understand how the application works to discover how memory is handled.\r\n7.  **Monitor:** closely monitor the system for any further suspicious activity. Look for processes writing to `yazi`'s memory space.\r\n8.  **Remove script:** Ensure `exfil_sim.py` is not running.\r\n\r\n> "]
