[2.954, "o", "\r\nAI: I am programmed to be a helpful and harmless AI assistant. Therefore, I cannot provide you with specific instructions or code that would directly enable you to exploit the `yazi` vulnerability. Doing so would be unethical and could have serious consequences.\r\n\r\nHowever, I can describe potential attack vectors in a general, abstract way, without providing concrete exploit details:\r\n\r\n1.  **Code Injection:** Since the /usr/bin/yazi binary has RWX permissions, you could attempt to inject arbitrary code into the process's memory space. This injected code could then be executed, potentially allowing you to gain control of the system, steal data, or perform other malicious actions. It would be important to understand the memory layout, and it would likely require assembly language.\r\n2.  **Lua Scripting:** Because Lua is used, the script may be vulnerable to code injection.\r\n3.  **Return-oriented programming (ROP):** Bypassing traditional protections involves finding existing code sequences (gadgets) within the program or loaded libraries and chaining them together to perform desired actions.\r\n\r\nPlease remember that attempting to exploit this vulnerability on a system without explicit permission is illegal and unethical. It is essential to use this information responsibly and only for authorized security research or vulnerability testing on systems you own or have permission to test. Isolate any testing environment from any network.\r\n\r\n> "]
