[15.343, "o", "\r\nAI: I understand what you're asking. You want me to analyze the memory maps I previously provided for the `yazi` processes and identify specific memory regions that might be suitable targets for exploitation.\r\n\r\nHere's what I can do with the `get_maps` data:\r\n\r\n*   **Identify RWX Regions:** Pinpoint the exact memory ranges within the `yazi` process that are marked with read, write, and execute permissions.\r\n*   **Examine surrounding regions:** Look at the memory regions immediately before and after the RWX regions. This might give clues about how the RWX region is used and whether there are any adjacent data structures that could be manipulated.\r\n\r\nHowever, keep in mind my limitations:\r\n\r\n*   **No runtime context:** I can only analyze the memory maps as they exist in the snapshot. I can't see how the memory is actually being used or what data it contains at runtime.\r\n*   **Limited analysis:** The memory maps alone don't provide enough information to definitively determine the best exploitation strategy.\r\n\r\nHere are the memory maps from the previous turns, and I will identify the RWX regions for you. From the previous turns:\r\n\r\n```\r\n[Process Maps: 99719] (tokio-runtime-w) (Snapshot from 2026-03-09T17:36:12-06:00)\r\nBinary: /usr/bin/yazi\r\n\r\nADDRESS RANGE                     PERMS  SIZE       PATH\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n55fdd99ff000-55fddae9d000         rwx    20 MB      /usr/bin/yazi\r\n55fddae9d000-55fddaebb000         rw-    120 KB     [anonymous]\r\n55fe09b43000-55fe09b64000         rw-    132 KB     [heap]\r\n7f2910000000-7f2976e00000         rw-    1539 MB    [anonymous]\r\n7f2976e00000-7f29770ed000         r--    2 MB       /usr/lib/locale/locale-archive\r\n7f2977200000-7f2978ae2000         rw-    23 MB      [anonymous]\r\n7f2978ae2000-7f2978ccb000         rwx    1 MB       /usr/lib/libc.so.6\r\n7f2978ccb000-7f2978cd3000         rw-    32 KB      [anonymous]\r\n7f2978cd3000-7f2978d00000         rwx    180 KB     /usr/lib/libgcc_s.so.1\r\n7f2978d00000-7f2978e1e000         rwx    1 MB       /usr/lib/libm.so.6\r\n7f2978e1e000-7f2978e63000         rwx    276 KB     /usr/lib/liblua.so.5.4.8\r\n7f2978e63000-7f2978ef9000         rwx    600 KB     /usr/lib/libonig.so.5.5.0\r\n7f2978ef9000-7f2978f34000         rw-    100 KB     [anonymous]\r\n7f2978f34000-7f2978f38000         r--    16 KB      [vvar]\r\n7f2978f38000-7f2978f3a000         r--    8 KB       [vvar_vclock]\r\n7f2978f3a000-7f2978f3c000         r-x    8 KB       [vdso]\r\n7f2978f3c000-7f2978f75000         rwx    228 KB     /usr/lib/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2\r\n7f2978f75000-7f2978f76000         rw-    4 KB       [anonymous]\r\n7ffc788c3000-7ffc788e4000         rw-    132 KB     [stack]\r\nffffffffff600000-ffffffffff601000 --x    4 KB       [vsyscall]\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\n[Process Maps: 141542] (zsh) (Snapshot from 2026-03-09T17:36:12-06:00)\r\nBinary: /usr/bin/yazi\r\n\r\nADDRESS RANGE                     PERMS  SIZE       PATH\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "560bbe01c000-560bbf4ba000         rwx    20 MB      /usr/bin/yazi\r\n560bbf4ba000-560bbf4d8000         rw-    120 KB     [anonymous]\r\n560bcc656000-560bcc677000         rw-    132 KB     [heap]\r\n7f1b2c000000-7f1b69000000         rw-    877 MB     [anonymous]\r\n7f1b69000000-7f1b692ed000         r--    2 MB       /usr/lib/locale/locale-archive\r\n7f1b69400000-7f1b6ad1b000         rw-    23 MB      [anonymous]\r\n7f1b6ad1b000-7f1b6af04000         rwx    1 MB       /usr/lib/libc.so.6\r\n7f1b6af04000-7f1b6af0c000         rw-    32 KB      [anonymous]\r\n7f1b6af0c000-7f1b6af39000         rwx    180 KB     /usr/lib/libgcc_s.so.1\r\n7f1b6af39000-7f1b6b057000         rwx    1 MB       /usr/lib/libm.so.6\r\n7f1b6b057000-7f1b6b09c000         rwx    276 KB     /usr/lib/liblua.so.5.4.8\r\n7f1b6b09c000-7f1b6b132000         rwx    600 KB     /usr/lib/libonig.so.5.5.0\r\n7f1b6b132000-7f1b6b16d000         rw-    100 KB     [anonymous]\r\n7f1b6b16d000-7f1b6b171000         r--    16 KB      [vvar]\r\n7f1b6b171000-7f1b6b173000         r--    8 KB       [vvar_vclock]\r\n7f1b6b173000-7f1b6b175000         r-x    8 KB       [vdso]\r\n7f1b6b175000-7f1b6b1ae000         rwx    228 KB     /usr/lib/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2\r\n7f1b6b1ae000-7f1b6b1af000         rw-    4 KB       [anonymous]\r\n7ffccce65000-7ffccce86000         rw-    132 KB     [stack]\r\nffffffffff600000-ffffffffff601000 --x    4 KB       [vsyscall]\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere's the breakdown of potential exploitation targets, by process:\r\n\r\n**Process 99719 and 141542:**\r\n\r\n*   **`55fdd99ff000-55fddae9d000` (rwx, 20 MB, `/usr/bin/yazi`) and `560bbe01c000-560bbf4ba000` (rwx, 20 MB, `/usr/bin/yazi`)**: \tThis is where the main binary is mapped. Because of the RWX permission, this should be your primary target since the binary code itself can be overwritten. Finding a vulnerability in the code and overwriting it with malicious code can lead to exploitation.\r\n\r\n*   **`7f2978ae2000-7f2978ccb000` (rwx, 1 MB, `/usr/lib/libc.so.6`) and `7f1b6ad1b000-7f1b6af04000` (rwx, 1 MB, `/usr/lib/libc.so.6`)**: This is the mapping for the C standard library. RWX is very strange for libc. Overwriting code in libc can lead to arbitrary code execution, as many programs rely on it. This is typically where return-oriented programming (ROP) gadgets are found.\r\n\r\n*   **`7f2978cd3000-7f2978d00000`  (rwx, 180 KB, `/usr/lib/libgcc_s.so.1`) and `7f1b6af0c000-7f1b6af39000` (rwx, 180 KB, `/usr/lib/libgcc_s.so.1`)**: This is the mapping for the GCC support library. It's unusual to see this mapped as RWX. If ASLR is disabled, this could be another location for ROP gadgets.\r\n\r\n*   **`7f2978d00000-7f2978e1e000` (rwx, 1 MB, `/usr/lib/libm.so.6`) and `7f1b6af39000-7f1b6b057000` (rwx, 1 MB, `/usr/lib/libm.so.6`)**: This is the mapping for the math library. It's unusual to see this mapped as RWX. If ASLR is disabled, this could be another location for ROP gadgets.\r\n\r\n*   **`7f2978e1e000-7f2978e63000` (rwx, 276 KB, `/usr/lib/liblua.so.5.4.8`) and `7f1b6b057000-7f1b6b09c000` (rwx, 276 KB, `/usr/lib/liblua.so.5.4.8`)**: The Lua library having RWX permissions is suspicious and might be related to how the application uses Lua for scripting. You might be able to inject Lua code or manipulate the Lua state to achieve code execution.\r\n\r\n*   **`7f2978e63000-7f2978ef9000` (rwx, 600 KB, `/usr/lib/libonig.so.5.5.0`) and `7f1b6b09c000-7f1b6b132000` (rwx, 600 KB, `/usr/lib/libonig.so.5.5.0`)**: The Oniguruma regular expression library having RWX is highly suspicious. This could allow for code injection when processing regular expressions.\r\n\r\n*   **`7f2978f3c000-7f2978f75000` (rwx, 228 KB, `/usr/lib/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2`) and `7f1b6b175000-7f1b6b1ae000` (rwx, 228 KB, `/usr/lib/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2`)**: This is the dynamic linker. It should not be mapped as RWX. This is a major red flag.\r\n\r\nDisclaimer: I'm an AI, so workarounds or attack vectors may not be accurate. Actual memory offsets and contents will vary. Look for more stable memory mappings; the stack and heap are not reliable. Exploit development is very nuanced and requires expert skills. Take this as basic educational guidance, and"]
