[4.091, "o", "\r\nAI: Indeed, the Chrome process (PID 1736) has made 160 connections to `157.240.25.60:443 (whatsapp-cdn-shv-02-qro1.fbcdn.net)`, and its child (PID 1790) has made 29 connections to the same address. This confirms that Chrome is also connecting to the WhatsApp CDN. The parent of 1736 is pid 1 which is the init process.\r\n\r\nThe user also has `/home/raul/.config/google-chrome/Default/IndexedDB/https_web.whatsapp.com_0.indexeddb.blob` opened so the user is actively using WhatsApp web.\r\n\r\nThe file opens for pid 1736 also include `accounts.google.com`, `play.google.com`, `www.google-analytics.com`, `chatgpt.com`, `analytics.google.com`, `gnar.grammarly.com`, `capi.grammarly.com`, `auth.grammarly.com`, `gemini.google.com`, `signaler-pa.clients6.google.com`, and `www.google.com`.\r\n\r\nGiven this information, the connections to the WhatsApp CDN are likely legitimate. It's highly probable that Raul is using WhatsApp Web in Chrome, which would explain the connections to the WhatsApp CDN. I apologize for the previous misdirection. It seems my initial assessment was too quick to jump to a malicious conclusion. There are many web app hosts for `run/systemd/machines`: it seems like Chrome is running web apps as systemd \"machines\". Examining those more would be interesting.\r\n\r\nI can investigate the Chrome extensions, if you want (`/home/raul/.config/google-chrome/Default/Extensions`).\r\n\r\n\r\n> "]
